author: @EranM
text: This is how you quickly investigate your results:  1) I would suggest to train until a certain point in time and test after that point. After all, this is a sequential data and not random observations.  I've tested the score and its looks like this:  clf.score: 0.703125 (need to read implementation to understand this score) AUC: 0.758748674443 Precision: 0.55   2) I would use an AUC metric to evaluate how good this model learns. 3) After using a precision (tp / (tp + fp)) and got such a low score of 0.55 I decided to print a confusion_matrix. 4) confusion_matrix results:      0    1 0 | 23 18 1 |  1   22  Which means i can predict 0 with precision of 95% and predict 1 with precision of 55%. So this model is REALLY GOOD for predicting FALLS, and close to RANDOM in predicting RISES.   Conclusion: Model is good to predict falls of HPI.  All in all, GREAT SERIES sentdex !!!

author: @ConnerDKnox
text: Hi Harrison!  Big fan of your videos, I hadn't had time to work through all the code on my own yet but was wondering what sort of accuracy you get if you simply always predict increases as the HPI has somewhat steadily increased over time?  As best I can tell the scoring is the percentage of predictions that the model correctly predicted, so might it even make sense to look at the models score as (% correct model prediction - % correct always increase prediction)/(1-% correct always increase prediction)? Thanks a ton for the work you put into these videos!
